default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultSince 2006 we have attempted to continue recording Lost Ways but have encountered difficulties in pursuing the public’s rights.  The most arduous of these is the work required to justify DMMO claims at Public Inquiries (PI’s).  Objections to the DMMO process require the Planning Inspectorate (PIN’s) to become involved and many days of their time can be spent determining the facts of the case for correcting the Definitive Map and Statement (DMS). We 
defaultwou
defaultld 
defaultlike to see this process 
defaultfurther 
defaultsimplified 
defaultand believe the SWG is the forum to seek further deregulation. 
defaultThe Cost of Maintenance and Repair of Byways.default•
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe standard of ‘good repair’ for BOATs and unsealed roads, and the cost of repair, is an issue that has been debated for many years. It is our experience (and that of horse-riders as regards bridleways, and walkers as regards footpaths) that highway authorities often put a price on maintenance and repair far in excess of what it costs in the ‘real world’. Where volunteers get 
defaultinvolved,
default or local small contractors, perfectly good jobs are done at a small fraction of authority estimates. 
default•
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultGLASS provides finance and volunteers to The 
defaultTreadlightly
default Trust which is a UK charity set up to educate and inform stakeholders in public all 
defaultpurpose  rights
default of way.  
defaultTreadlightly
default has been able to repair many ROW for the cost of materials alone and with its association of trained Ambassadors and volunteer workforce has been able to show some significant improvements on 
defaultunsurfaced
default routes around the UK.
default•
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe 
defaultTreadlightly
default Trust has commissioned costing information from such bodies as the Forestry 
defaultCommision
default Wales.  Their maintenance and repair cost for the forestry tracks used by their heavy equipment and it is a fraction of the costs of Highway Authorities road maintenance cost.  This is in part due to the nature of the work done and the specification standards adopted by forestry officials.   
default•
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultGLASS requests your Committee to note that other bodies are proposing the downgrading of vehicular ways to Restricted Byways on the basis of excessive costs to repair. Their figures are greatly exaggerated. Most Highway Authorities have spent little or nothing on their byways in the last 50 years yet they remain usable by all parties. Ongoing maintenance cost is not in itself a reason for closure.
default•
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWe ask you to also note that Restricted Byways would still require maintenance as they are full width roads with their major users being agriculture and property access. Your Governments own investigation found that recreational use of byways is only about one third of the total so removing it would make little difference to cost of repair.
defaultWe would be please to provide further more detailed evidence should you 
defaultcommittee require it.
default14 September 2013
